<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="403" pageId="0" pageNumber="401" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,700,2014,2036]" box="[151,700,2014,2036]" pageId="0" pageNumber="401">Station: AB 191 (MNHN S2 BAT.B 35; slide S2. 770)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">
Two specimens 
<quantity box="[337,395,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[455,513,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="3.0">3mm</quantity>
large were attached to a piece of dead coral. The body is dome-like (
<figureCitation box="[1330,1422,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), bright red and covered with spicules. The siphons are well apart, not protruding, opening in a slit; their internal tunic contains smaller sizes of the same spicules as those at the body surface. The body wall is thin colourless in formalin (
<figureCitation box="[265,380,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Fig. 1B,C</figureCitation>
), with a musculature in bundles radiating from the siphons to the body sides and becoming thinner transversally. The oral tentacles are of 2 sizes: 8 poorly branched and smaller simple ones intercalated. The dorsal lamina is made of pointed languets. The branchial sac has 6 high folds on each side (
<figureCitation box="[1250,1344,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). Spiral stigmata make deep infundibula. The formula of the larger specimen is: ER (11)1(12)1(13)1(13)1(10)1(10) DL (10)1(10)1(12)1(12)1(10)1(7)1 E L.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" startId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" targetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1973,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1973,1995]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Millar &amp; Goodbody" authorityYear="1974" box="[281,470,1973,1996]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="goreaui">
<emphasis box="[281,470,1973,1996]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Bathypera goreaui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">
The digestive loop is long and opened (
<figureCitation box="[649,731,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">Fig.1D</figureCitation>
). The stomach has a thin wall with a large lobed diverticulum on each side (
<figureCitation box="[309,400,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). The intestine is isodiametric ending in a smooth anus. The digestive loop is linked to the body wall. There is one elongated gonad on each side (
<figureCitation box="[768,855,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[217,1365,473,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[217,1369,473,1958]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bathypera goreaui. A, one specimen, scale bar = 2mm; B,C, dorsal and ventral sides of a specimen without tunic; D, dissection (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
) attached to the body wall; the left gonad is located inside the gut loop. The ovary is tubular sided by 2 series of testis vesicles. The gonoducts are short and linked together at the tip of the gonad. Small endocarps are irregularly placed on each side of the body wall.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">
The spicules 35µ in diameter have the characteristic shape of the genus with a basal disc below a spherical bulb erect in triangular spines of equal length. The specimens from Martinique correspond in all points to the original description. They constitute the second record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Millar &amp; Goodbody" authorityYear="1974" box="[706,823,405,428]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="goreaui">
<emphasis box="[706,823,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">B. goreaui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Caribbean region from where they probably are native. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1904" box="[358,474,440,464]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[358,474,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">Bathypera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains only 4 other species all from the Arctic or Antarctic deep seas. All differ in having a stomach with longitudinal folds and without diverticula. 
<taxonomicName authority="Michaelsen, 1904" authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1904" box="[886,1233,476,501]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[886,1027,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">B. splendens</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1035,1233,476,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" refId="ref8207" refString="Michaelsen, W. (1904) Die stolidobranchiaten Ascidien der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition auf dem Dampfer &quot; Faldivia &quot; 1898 - 1899, 7, 182 - 260" type="journal article">Michaelsen, 1904</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Vinogradova, 1962" authorityName="Vinogradova" authorityYear="1962" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hastaefera">
<emphasis box="[1287,1435,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">B. hastaefera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[151,365,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" refId="ref9588" refString="Vinogradova, N. G. (1962) Ascidiae simplices of the Indian part of the Antarctic. Biological Resultsof the Soviet Antarctic Expedition (1955 - 1958). Explorations of the fauna of the seas Acad S. USSR Zoological Institute, 1, 195 - 215." type="journal article">Vinogradova, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
have 6 branchial folds on each side. 
<taxonomicName authority="Young &amp; Vazquez, 1995" authorityName="Young &amp; Vazquez" authorityYear="1995" box="[774,1199,511,536]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="feminalba">
<emphasis box="[774,917,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">B. feminalba</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[923,1199,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" refId="ref9639" refString="Young, C. M. &amp; Vazquez, E. (1995) Morphology, larval development and distribution of Bathypera feminalba n. sp. (Ascidiacea: Pyuridae) a deep-water ascidian from the fjords and sounds of British Columbia. Invertebrate Biology, 114, 89 - 106. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3226958" type="journal article">Young &amp; Vázquez, 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has 7 branchial folds and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ritter, 1907" authorityName="Ritter" authorityYear="1907" box="[198,458,548,573]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ovoidea">
<emphasis box="[198,318,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">B. ovoidea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[325,458,548,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" refId="ref9023" refString="Ritter, W. E. (1907) The ascidians collected by the United States Fisheries Bureau steamer Albatross on the coast of California during the summer of 1904. University California Publications in Zoology, 4, 1 - 52. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 1573" type="journal article">Ritter, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has 9 branchial folds on each side.
</paragraph>
